node.text:
In the past, I didn’t want to feel the impact of trauma-and so I stuffed it down. 
.
I thought that I was ‘fine’ until I clearly wasn’t.
.
My attempts at numbing out and ‘finding safety’ through ED behaviors took over my life and made me miserable, depressed, and a shell of my former self.
.
It turned out I needed therapy and safe relationships to truly heal. 
.
Avoiding my feelings only made them stronger-and made me dependent on all of these behaviors to try to numb out. 
.

node.text:
The best weight range for you is the one that enables you to live your most authentic and joyful life.
.
@paigepayne_creations did the art for this and is also just a wonderful human. Appreciate her 💕
.
If you have to restrict food, obsessively exercise, or purge to maintain a certain weight-that’s not the right weight for you. I know this can be hard to sit with, especially for those who face weight stigma due to their size AND you deserve so much more than a life spent suppressing your natural weight, and ultimately suppressing your life experiences.
.
We all only get one life-and I want you to eventually be able to experience it more fully. 💕
.
**and we have to acknowledge how weight stigma and oppression towards marginalized folks can impact their life experiences. 
.

May be an image of text that says 'Jennifer Rollin @jennifer_rollin Harvard did an 100 year study and found that the people who lived the longest, were those with the most connected relationships. So going to grab ice cream with a friend is generally healthier than eating a plate of carrots alone.'.

node.text:
Plus a plate of carrots may be filling but not very satisfying and also won’t have long ‘staying power’ in terms of hunger due to the lack of fat etc. So if you’re craving veggies far better to pair them with ranch, hummus, butter, etc. (as this also helps with the absorption of fat-soluble nutrients). 
.
Anyway, point being that social connections were found in an 100 year study by Harvard to be the biggest predictor of health and longevity. 
.
If you don’t have a ton of friends, don’t use this to beat yourself up! Just use it as recovery motivation as EDs can really isolate you.
.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jennifer Rollin, MSW, LCSW-C on August 07, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Jennifer Rollin @jennifer_rollin One potential function of Ûan disorder symptoms is that they address the hyperarousal symptoms of trauma. So you may using eating disorder behaviors as a way to cope with trauma related symptoms.'.

node.text:
We all have a window of tolerance where we feel most regulated. Above and below that window are hyper and hypo arousal.
.
Hyperarousal: easily startled, anxious, restless, trouble sleeping etc.
.
Hypoarousal: depressed, lethargic, dissociated etc.
.
Sometimes eating disorder behaviors are subconscious attempts to cope with trauma related symptoms where temporary relief can be achieved by under- or over-eating (however, we know that these behaviors lead to long term misery and reduced life experiences).
.
“For example, in anorexia, restricting food intake results in numbing of emotion and sensation. Over-eating also results in numbing accompanied by relaxation, increased parasympathetic hypoarousal, disconnection from the body, spaciness, or drowsiness. Bulimia, too, in both the binging and purging phases, causes a reduction in hyperarousal and decreased pain sensitivity via activation of the dorsal vagal system (Faris et al., 2008), the same branch of the parasympathetic nervous system implicated in total collapse and feigned death survival responses.” Via Janina Fisher in Healing The Fragmented Selves of Trauma Survivors.
.
This helps to give us information in being able to learn more about the potential function of your behaviors and then to find more values aligning ways of calming your nervous system when you are in a state of hyperarousal.
.
Therapy can be really helpful in terms of addressing both trauma and ED symptoms!
.

May be an image of food and text that says 'የማপ Jennifer Rollin @jennifer_rollin There's something beautiful you experience after an eating disorder. When a handful of gummies is just a handful of gummies. And French toast is just delicious and warm as you eat it in bed with your partner. Not X calories or X carbs. Hold on for that day.'.

node.text:
All I wanted in my eating disorder (at certain points) was just to be able to eat normally and not be so anxious around food.
.
And now, that I get to experience that I’ll never take it for granted.
.
I watched a reality show weeks ago when one of the woman’s new fiancé made her French toast. She complained that ‘it wasn’t healthy’ and basically ruined the moment. 
.
Eating disorders and diet culture shrink people’s lives and steal moments.
.
You deserve so much more than that!
.
